<body>
  <h1>NyayaSetu Modules Working Plan</h1>
  <p><b>Purpose:</b> This document explains the detailed working plan for NyayaSetu modules so different team members can understand, divide, and implement the platform in phases.</p>
  <p><b>Product Context:</b> NyayaSetu is planned as a web platform first and later as a mobile app. The future vision is a professional justice network: part legal-services marketplace, part legal awareness platform, part advocate professional network, and part secure help-seeking system. It can borrow interaction patterns from LinkedIn and X, but the content must stay focused on Nyaya, justice, rights, legal awareness, social issues, public interest, and professional help rather than memes or casual entertainment.</p>

  <h1>1. Updated Product Understanding</h1>
  <p>NyayaSetu should not be treated as only a lawyer directory. The stronger idea is to build a trusted justice network where citizens, advocates, law students, NGOs, legal educators, and institutions can interact around legal awareness and real legal help.</p>
  <p>The platform has four major layers:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><b>Access layer:</b> Citizens can ask AI questions, understand legal problems, find advocates, request consultations, message privately, and track help requests.</li>
    <li><b>Professional layer:</b> Advocates can create verified profiles, publish useful legal content, receive qualified leads, manage requests, and build reputation.</li>
    <li><b>Community layer:</b> Users can post justice-focused updates, legal news, articles, awareness posts, and help-seeking posts.</li>
    <li><b>Trust layer:</b> Admins verify advocates, moderate posts, handle reports, manage disputes, and protect users from misinformation or abuse.</li>
  </ul>

  <h1>2. Major Requirement Changes After New Context</h1>
  <p class="note">The core idea does not need to change. But the LinkedIn/X-style justice network adds some important product requirements beyond UI.</p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Area</th><th>Change Needed</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
    <tr><td>UI/UX</td><td>Moderate change</td><td>The platform should feel like a serious professional network, not only a dashboard app.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Justice Feed</td><td>Major addition</td><td>Posts, articles, legal news, awareness content, and help-seeking posts need their own module.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Moderation</td><td>Major addition</td><td>Justice-related posts can include misinformation, defamation, private data, fake legal advice, or sensitive claims.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Identity and Reputation</td><td>Major addition</td><td>Public posting requires verified identities, role badges, advocate badges, and profile credibility.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Notifications</td><td>Higher priority later</td><td>Posts, comments, follows, messages, mentions, and consultation requests all need notification flows.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Search</td><td>Higher priority later</td><td>Search must cover advocates, posts, articles, legal topics, cities, languages, and practice areas.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Mobile App Readiness</td><td>Important from start</td><td>Feed, chat, posting, directory, and dashboards must be mobile-first so a future app is easier to build.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h1>3. Prototype Goal</h1>
  <p>The prototype should not try to become the full company immediately. It should show the full potential clearly enough to convince mentors, early users, and investors.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>User lands on NyayaSetu and sees a professional justice-focused feed.</li>
    <li>User reads useful legal awareness posts from verified advocates.</li>
    <li>User asks the AI assistant a legal question.</li>
    <li>AI gives safe general information and suggests speaking with an advocate.</li>
    <li>User searches verified advocates.</li>
    <li>User opens an advocate profile and sends a consultation request.</li>
    <li>Advocate receives the lead in the dashboard.</li>
    <li>Admin can verify advocates and moderate the platform.</li>
  </ol>

  <h1>4. Module-Level Working Plan</h1>

  <h2>Module 1: Authentication, Identity, and Role Routing</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Frontend + Backend/Supabase Developer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>This module controls who the user is and what experience they receive. It supports clients, advocates, admins, and future public/community users. Identity is very important because the platform includes public posts, legal help, private messaging, and verified professional profiles.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>User signup and login using Supabase Auth or equivalent.</li>
    <li>Role selection during onboarding: Client, Advocate, Admin.</li>
    <li>Basic profile creation with name, email, role, city, language preference, and avatar placeholder.</li>
    <li>Redirect user to the correct dashboard after login.</li>
    <li>Protect routes so only correct roles can access certain pages.</li>
    <li>Logout and session persistence.</li>
    <li>Basic profile edit screen.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>Phone OTP login and Google OAuth.</li>
    <li>Password reset and email verification.</li>
    <li>Multi-factor authentication.</li>
    <li>Account deletion request.</li>
    <li>Device and session management.</li>
    <li>Login activity history and suspicious login detection.</li>
    <li>DPDP-aligned consent management.</li>
    <li>Separate public profile identity and private account identity.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Working Flow</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>User opens signup.</li>
    <li>User selects role.</li>
    <li>System creates auth account and profile row.</li>
    <li>User is redirected to the proper dashboard.</li>
    <li>Protected routes check session and role before rendering.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Module 2: Public Landing Page and Pitch Experience</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Frontend/UI Designer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>The landing page must quickly explain the mission: NyayaSetu bridges people to justice using AI, verified advocates, legal awareness, and secure consultation workflows.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>Professional landing page with trust-focused design.</li>
    <li>Clear headline around access to justice.</li>
    <li>CTA buttons: Ask AI Legal Assistant, Find an Advocate, Join as Advocate.</li>
    <li>Sections for verified advocates, legal awareness, secure communication, and consultation requests.</li>
    <li>Preview of justice feed with legal awareness posts.</li>
    <li>Mobile responsive first screen.</li>
    <li>Careful language that does not promise legal outcomes.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>SEO pages for legal topics.</li>
    <li>City and practice-area landing pages.</li>
    <li>Blog and legal awareness content.</li>
    <li>Advocate acquisition funnel.</li>
    <li>Partnership pages, press kit, testimonials, and conversion analytics.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Module 3: Justice Feed, Posts, Articles, and Public Knowledge Layer</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Frontend + Backend Developer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>This is the LinkedIn/X-inspired layer. It turns NyayaSetu from a static directory into a living justice network. The content should be useful, serious, and connected to law, rights, news, civic issues, and help-seeking.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>Feed page after login.</li>
    <li>Post composer for short posts.</li>
    <li>Post types: short update, article, legal news, help request.</li>
    <li>Feed cards with author name, role badge, verification badge, timestamp, category, and content.</li>
    <li>Support/like button.</li>
    <li>Basic comments or comment placeholder.</li>
    <li>Save/share placeholder.</li>
    <li>Topic tags: Consumer Rights, Property, Family Law, Employment, Criminal Law, Women Safety, RTI, Tenant Rights.</li>
    <li>Advocate posts show professional badge.</li>
    <li>Help-seeking posts include warning not to reveal confidential details publicly.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>Rich-text articles.</li>
    <li>Image/document/media upload with moderation.</li>
    <li>Mentions and hashtags.</li>
    <li>Follow system.</li>
    <li>Reposts and quote posts.</li>
    <li>Bookmarks.</li>
    <li>Advanced comments and replies.</li>
    <li>Feed ranking algorithm.</li>
    <li>Topic communities.</li>
    <li>Verified legal news sources and fact-check labels.</li>
    <li>Misinformation reporting and legal sensitivity warnings.</li>
    <li>NGO, law school, and institution accounts.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Working Flow</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>User opens feed.</li>
    <li>User reads legal updates and awareness posts.</li>
    <li>Advocate publishes educational post.</li>
    <li>User reacts, saves, or comments.</li>
    <li>If user needs help, CTA routes to AI assistant or advocate discovery.</li>
    <li>Admin can moderate posts when reported.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Module 4: User and Advocate Public Profiles</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Frontend + Backend Developer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>Profiles create credibility. Advocates need LinkedIn-like professional identity. Users need safe participation without exposing sensitive legal problems by default.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>Public advocate profile with name, avatar, bio, city, languages, practice areas, experience, fee estimate, and verification badge.</li>
    <li>Basic user profile showing name, role, city, and posts.</li>
    <li>Advocate activity tab showing posts/articles.</li>
    <li>Verification badge visible on profile and feed author card.</li>
    <li>Profile completion indicator for advocates.</li>
    <li>Edit profile flow for advocates.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>Professional portfolio.</li>
    <li>Education and certifications.</li>
    <li>Document/certification display.</li>
    <li>Public/private profile controls.</li>
    <li>Followers and following.</li>
    <li>Endorsements.</li>
    <li>Consultation stats and profile analytics.</li>
    <li>Institutional profiles for NGOs, legal clinics, law colleges, and public bodies.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Module 5: Advocate Directory / Marketplace</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Frontend + Backend Developer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>This module helps users find relevant advocates quickly and safely. It connects AI learning, feed awareness, and real consultation action.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>Advocate listing page.</li>
    <li>Advocate cards with name, practice area, location, experience, languages, fee, verification badge, and rating/mock rating.</li>
    <li>Search by name and practice area.</li>
    <li>Filters for practice area, city, experience, language, and verification status.</li>
    <li>View Profile button.</li>
    <li>Request Consultation button.</li>
    <li>Seeded demo advocates.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>Availability-based filtering.</li>
    <li>Fee range filter.</li>
    <li>Advanced ranking algorithm.</li>
    <li>Geo-location discovery.</li>
    <li>Recommendation engine.</li>
    <li>Response-time sorting.</li>
    <li>Real reviews and verified-only toggle.</li>
    <li>Sponsored visibility only after legal compliance review.</li>
    <li>Fake profile detection.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Module 6: Consultation Request and Booking Intake</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Full-Stack Developer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>Convert user interest into a structured lead for an advocate. For the prototype this should be a request flow, not a full paid booking system.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>Consultation request form.</li>
    <li>Fields: legal category, short problem description, city/state, urgency, preferred date/time, preferred mode, and language.</li>
    <li>Privacy warning not to share highly sensitive details publicly.</li>
    <li>Save request to database.</li>
    <li>Show request in client dashboard.</li>
    <li>Show request in advocate dashboard.</li>
    <li>Status values: Pending, Accepted, Rejected, Completed.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>Calendar slot selection.</li>
    <li>Payments before booking.</li>
    <li>Rescheduling and cancellation.</li>
    <li>Refund rules.</li>
    <li>No-show handling.</li>
    <li>Google Calendar sync.</li>
    <li>Email/SMS/WhatsApp reminders.</li>
    <li>Conflict-of-interest check.</li>
    <li>Engagement letter workflow.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Module 7: Client Dashboard</h2>
  <p class="meta">Owner Type: Frontend Developer</p>
  <h3>Purpose</h3>
  <p>The client dashboard is the user's home base for legal help. It should show active requests, AI assistance, saved advocates, messages, documents, and feed shortcuts.</p>
  <h3 class="green">Prototype / Build Now</h3>
  <ul class="green">
    <li>Welcome dashboard.</li>
    <li>Active consultation request cards.</li>
    <li>Recommended/saved advocates.</li>
    <li>Recent messages.</li>
    <li>AI assistant shortcut.</li>
    <li>Document placeholder.</li>
    <li>Latest legal awareness posts shortcut.</li>
    <li>Clear navigation.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3 class="red">Later / Full Platform</h3>
  <ul class="red">
    <li>Payment history.</li>
    <li>Consultation history.</li>
    <li>Case timeline.</li>
    <li>Document vault.</li>
    <li>AI conversation history.</li>
    <li>Court date reminders.</li>
    <li>Refund/dispute requests.</li>
    <li>Invoices.</li>
    <li>Multi-language dashboard.</li>
  </ul>

